{"title_page": "Neelam Kothari", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian actress}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image              = NeelamKothari.jpg\n| caption            = Neelam  Soni Khotari in 2009\n| imagesize          = \n| name               = Neelam  Kothari Soni\n| birth_name         = Neelam Kothari\n| othername          = Neelam Soni\n| birth_place        = [[Hong Kong]]\n| birth_date         = \n| yearsactive        = 1984\u20132001\n| spouse             = Rishi Sethia (divorced)<br/>[[Samir Soni]] (2011\u2013present)\n| children           = Ahana Soni\n| parents            = Parveen Kothari (mother)<br/>Shishir Kothari (father)\n| occupation         = [[Actress]]<br/> [[Jewelry designer]]\n| residence          = [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n}}\n\n'''Neelam Kothari Soni''' is an Indian jewellery designer and former actress. She made her acting debut with ''Jawaani'' (1984) opposite debutant Karan Shah. She then starred opposite [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]] in ''[[Love 86]]'' (1986), ''Sindoor'' (1986), ''[[Khudgarz]]'' (1987), ''[[Hatya]]'' (1988), ''Farz Ki Jung'', (1989), ''[[Taaqatwar]]'' (1989) and ''[[Do Qaidi]]'' (1989). She starred opposite [[Chunkey Pandey]] in films ''[[Aag Hi Aag]]'' (1987), ''[[Paap Ki Duniya]]'' (1988), ''[[Khatron Ke Khiladi (1988 film)|Khatron Ke Khiladi]]'' (1988), ''[[Ghar Ka Chiraag]]'' (1989), and ''[[Mitti Aur Sona]]'' (1989).\n\nHer career's biggest hit remains ''[[Ghar Ka Chiraag]]'' opposite [[Rajesh Khanna]] in 1989.\n\n==Early life==\nNeelam Kothari was born in [[Hong Kong]]. She is a [[Gujarati people|Gujarati]]-[[Iran]]ian.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-neelam-kothari-and-samir-soni-get-candid-about-their-upcoming-wedding-1492601 |title=Neelam Kothari and Samir Soni get candid about their upcoming wedding |first=Ismat |last=Tahseen |date=10 January 2011 |publisher=[[Daily News and Analysis|DNA India]]}}</ref> As a child, she learnt to play the keyboard and danced Jazz Ballet. Her family has a traditional jewellery making business, making high-class pieces. She was educated at [[Island School]], where she was a member of Rutherford house. After her childhood in Hong Kong, her family moved to Bangkok. Neelam was holidaying in Mumbai when she was approached by director Ramesh Behl.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.window2india.com/cms/admin/article.jsp?aid=9145 |title=NRI beauties making it big in Bollywood |work=window2india.com}}</ref> She decided to give acting a shot and signed for the film [[Jawaani|''Jawaani'' (1984)]] alongside Karan Shah, [[Tina Munim]]'s nephew.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.screenindia.com/old/20020426/fcover.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=29 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081022114050/http://www.screenindia.com/old/20020426/fcover.html |archivedate=22 October 2008 }}</ref> But the film was a major flop commercially.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.screenindia.com/old/20020426/fcover.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=29 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081022114050/http://www.screenindia.com/old/20020426/fcover.html |archivedate=22 October 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHer [[performance]] in her debut film was noticed in film circles and she received offers. She later became famous in 1986 for her role in the film ''[[Ilzaam]]'' opposite another debutant, [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]]. She made a popular pairing with Govinda and starred with him in 14 movies and some of their films include ''[[Love 86]]'' (1986), ''[[Khudgarz]]'' (1987), ''[[Hatya]]'' (1988) and ''[[Taaqatwar]]'' (1989). She had 5 hits opposite [[Chunkey Pandey]], such as ''[[Aag Hi Aag]]'' (1987), ''[[Paap Ki Duniya]]'' (1988), ''[[Khatron Ke Khiladi (1988 film)|Khatron Ke Khiladi]]'' (1988), ''[[Mitti Aur Sona]]'' (1989)  and ''[[Ghar Ka Chiraag]]'' (1989). She also worked in the Bengali film ''Badnaam'' (1990).\n\nShe was also noticed for her appearance in the 1998 film ''[[Kuch Kuch Hota Hai]]'', where she played herself as a [[VJ (media personality)|VJ]]. Her last film was the 1999 ensemble family drama ''[[Hum Saath Saath Hain]]'' in which she played a supporting role. Her last film was the delayed release ''Kasam'' in 2001, opposite [[Chunky Pandey]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/We-had-loads-to-sort-out-before-marriage-Neelam/articleshow/7358538.cms |title=We had loads to sort out before marriage: Neelam |work=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Sameer Soni,Neelam Kothari grace Kallista Spa opening 08.jpg|thumb|right|Neelam Kothari with husband [[Samir Soni]] at grace Kallista Spa opening.|272x272px]] \nIn October 2000, Neelam married Rishi Sethia in Bangkok, son of a businessman from the U.K.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/eyecatchers/story/20001106-actor-neelam-kothari-and-beau-rishi-sethia-get-married-in-bangkok-778400-2000-11-06 |title=Actor Neelam Kothari and beau Rishi Sethia get married in Bangkok |website=India Today |language=en |access-date=17 May 2018}}</ref> Their marriage was short-lived.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/neelam-kothari-splits-with-beau/story-kJLZpgnUpuUGvrSlW74JRL.html |title=Neelam Kothari splits with beau |date=6 November 2009 |work=www.hindustantimes.com |access-date=17 May 2018 |language=en}}</ref> On 24 January 2011, she married actor [[Samir Soni]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-neelam-weds-samir-soni/20110124.htm |title=Samir Soni weds Neelam |date=24 January 2011 |work=Rediff}}</ref> After 2 years of marriage, they decided to adopt a daughter on 2 September 2013 and named her Ahana.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Maheshwri |first1=Neha |title=Neelam and Samir Soni adopt a baby girl |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Neelam-and-Samir-Soni-have-adopted-a-baby-girl-named-Ahana/articleshow/22222260.cms |website=[[The Times of India]] |accessdate=17 April 2016 |date=2 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Other works==\nNeelam featured in [[Bina Mistry]]'s ''Hot Hot Hot'' music video,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/1999/99jan09/saturday/head6.htm |title=The Tribune...Saturday Plus Head |website=www.tribuneindia.com |access-date=3 August 2017}}</ref> a song that is part of a compilation of dance hits in the 1995 BMG release, titled ''Channel [V] Hits: The Ultimate Dance Collection''. The song became a hit when it was featured as part of the soundtrack of ''[[Bend It Like Beckham]]'' (2002).\n\n==Controversy==\nIn 1998, Neelam was charged with poaching two blackbucks in Kankani during the filming of ''Hum Saath Saath Hain'' along with co-stars [[Salman Khan]], [[Saif Ali Khan]], [[Sonali Bendre]] and [[Tabu (actress)|Tabu]]. A lower court charged her with the others under the Wildlife Act and the IPC. She had filed a revision petition before a sessions court which discharged her of Section 51 (causing harm to wildlife) of the Wildlife Act and both of 147 (punishment for rioting) and 149 (unlawful assembly of persons) of the Indian Penal Code. The Rajasthan state government then filed a revision petition before the Rajasthan high court, which again added Section 149 against her, which it had dropped. In December 2012, the Jodhpur court summoned her along with all the accused for commencement of the trial with the revised charges on 4 February 2013. She was acquitted by the CJM court at Jhodpur on 5 April 2018.\n\n==Jewellery designing==\nEven while pursuing her career in acting, she was interested in jewellery designing and was involved in her family business. She pursued a formal course in jewellery-designing<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.jewellerycraze.com/top-jewellery-designers-in-india/ |title=Top 15 Jewellery Designers In India You Must Know |date=11 July 2017 |website=Jewellery Craze |language=en-US |access-date=27 December 2018}}</ref> in Mumbai and, after quitting films in 2001, started out commercially on her own under the name Neelam Jewels.<ref>[http://archive.gulfnews.com/articles/04/10/27/137191.html Gulfnews: The many faces of Neelam Kothari<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> She opened a showroom in Mumbai in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.verveonline.com/27/spotlight/neelam/neelam.shtml |title=Spotlight - Neelam Jewels |work=verveonline.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090301132349/http://www.verveonline.com/27/spotlight/neelam/neelam.shtml |archivedate=1 March 2009 }}</ref> She then launched her jewellery store in Mumbai on 25 August 2011 under the name Neelam Kothari Fine Jewels.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n!scope=\"col\"| Year\n!scope=\"col\"| Title\n!scope=\"col\"| Role\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Jawaani]]''\n|Sanam\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 1986\n| ''[[Ilzaam]]''\n|Aarti\n|\n|-\n|''Andaz Pyar Ka''\n|\n|\n|-\n|''[[Love 86]]''\n|Esha\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1987\n| ''[[Aag Hi Aag]]''\n|Aarti\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Khudgarz]]''\n|Jyoti\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\" | 1988\n| ''[[Taaqatwar]]''\n|Bijli\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Hatya]]''\n|Sapna\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Waqt Ki Awaz]]''\n|Dancer, Singer\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Ghar Mein Ram Gali Mein Shyam]]''\n|Jaya\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Khatron Ke Khiladi (1988 film)|Khatron Ke Khiladi]]''\n|Sunita\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Paap Ki Duniya]]''\n|Aarti\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Sindoor]]''\n|Lalita Kapoor\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | 1989\n| ''[[Gharana (1989 film)|Gharana]]''\n|Lalita\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Do Qaidi]]''\n|Neelu\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Ghar Ka Chiraag]]''\n|Kiran\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Hum Bhi Insaan Hain (1989 film)|Hum Bhi Insaan Hain]]''\n|Rekha\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Mitti Aur Sona]]''\n|Anupama\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"12\" | 1990\n| ''Vishnu Devaa''\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Mandira (film)|Mandira]]''\n| \n|[[Bengali language|Bengali]] film\n|-\n| ''[[Badnam]]''\n| Kajol\n|[[Bengali language|Bengali]] film\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Shankara (1991 film)|Shankara]]''\n| Seema\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Doodh Ka Karz]]''\n|Reshma\n|\n|-\n|''Upkar Dhoodhache''\n|Reshma\n|[[Marathi language|Marathi]] film\n|-\n| ''[[Chor Pe Mor]]''\n|Ritu\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Amiri Garibi]]''\n|Jyoti\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Agneepath (1990 film)|Agneepath]]''\n| Siksha Chavan\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Zakhm]]''\n|Aarti\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Billoo Badshah]]''\n|Jyoti\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Farz Ki Jung]]''\n|Kavita\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Dost Garibon Ka]]''\n|Rekha\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | 1991\n| ''Kasak''\n| Divya\n|\n|-\n| ''Meet Mere Man Ke''\n|\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Ranbhoomi]]''\n| Neelam\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Indrajeet]]''\n| Neelam\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Afsana Pyaar Ka]]''\n| Nikita\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 1992\n| ''[[Ek Ladka Ek Ladki]]''\n| Renu / Rani\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Khule-Aam]]''\n| Priya\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Sahebzaade]]''\n| Chinar\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Laat Saab]]''\n| Anju / Mona\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" | 1993\n| ''[[Parampara (1993 film)|Parampara]]''\n| Sapna\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1995\n| ''[[Santaan]]''\n|Asha\n|\n|-\n| ''Antim Nyay''\n|Rekha\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 1996\n| ''[[Ek Tha Raja]]''\n|Shilpa\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Sauda (film)|Sauda]]''\n|Jyoti\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Aadithya]]''\n| \n| [[Kannada language|Kannada]] film\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Mohabbat Aur Jung]]''\n| Priya\n|\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Kuch Kuch Hota Hai]]''\n| Herself as VJ Neelam\n| Special Appearance\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Hum Saath-Saath Hain: We Stand United]]''\n| Sangeeta\n|\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''Pattar Aur Payal''\n|\n|\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Kasam (2001 film)|Kasam]]''\n| Bindiya\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Neelam Kothari}}\n* [http://www.neelamjewels.com/ Neelam Jewelers official website]\n* {{IMDb name|id=0624174|name=Neelam}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kothari, Neelam}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Hindi cinema]]\n[[Category:Indian jewellery designers]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Indian women designers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian designers]]\n[[Category:Artists from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Island School]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian designers]]\n[[Category:Gujarati people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian actress}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image              = NeelamKothari.jpg\n| caption            = Neelam  Soni Khotari in 2009\n| imagesize          = \n| name               = Neelam  Kothari Soni\n| birth_name         = Neelam Kothari\n| othername          = Neelam Soni\n| birth_place        = [[Hong Kong]]\n| birth_date         = \n| yearsactive        = 1984\u20132001\n| spouse             = Rishi Sethia (divorced)<br/>[[Samir Soni]] (2011\u2013present)\n| children           = Ahana Soni\n| parents            = Parveen Kothari (mother)<br/>Shishir Kothari (father)\n| occupation         = [[Actress]]<br/> [[Jewelry designer]]\n| residence          = [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n}}\n\n'''Neelam Kothari Soni''' is an Indian jewellery designer and former actress. She made her acting debut with ''Jawaani'' (1984) opposite debutant Karan Shah. She then starred opposite [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]] in ''[[Love 86]]'' (1986), ''Sindoor'' (1986), ''[[Khudgarz]]'' (1987), ''[[Hatya]]'' (1988), ''Farz Ki Jung'', (1989), ''[[Taaqatwar]]'' (1989) and ''[[Do Qaidi]]'' (1989). She starred opposite [[Chunkey Pandey]] in films ''[[Aag Hi Aag]]'' (1987), ''[[Paap Ki Duniya]]'' (1988), ''[[Khatron Ke Khiladi (1988 film)|Khatron Ke Khiladi]]'' (1988), ''[[Ghar Ka Chiraag]]'' (1989), and ''[[Mitti Aur Sona]]'' (1989).\n\nHer career's biggest hit remains ''[[Ghar Ka Chiraag]]'' opposite [[Rajesh Khanna]] in 1989.\n\n==Early life==\nNeelam Kothari was born in [[Hong Kong]]. She is a [[Gujarati people|Gujarati]]-[[Iran]]ian.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-neelam-kothari-and-samir-soni-get-candid-about-their-upcoming-wedding-1492601 |title=Neelam Kothari and Samir Soni get candid about their upcoming wedding |first=Ismat |last=Tahseen |date=10 January 2011 |publisher=[[Daily News and Analysis|DNA India]]}}</ref> As a child, she learnt to play the keyboard and danced Jazz Ballet. Her family has a traditional jewellery making business, making high-class pieces. She was educated at [[Island School]], where she was a member of Rutherford house. After her childhood in Hong Kong, her family moved to Bangkok. Neelam was holidaying in Mumbai when she was approached by director Ramesh Behl.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.window2india.com/cms/admin/article.jsp?aid=9145 |title=NRI beauties making it big in Bollywood |work=window2india.com}}</ref> She decided to give acting a shot and signed for the film [[Jawaani|''Jawaani'' (1984)]] alongside Karan Shah, [[Tina Munim]]'s nephew.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.screenindia.com/old/20020426/fcover.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=29 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081022114050/http://www.screenindia.com/old/20020426/fcover.html |archivedate=22 October 2008 }}</ref> But the film was a major flop commercially.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.screenindia.com/old/20020426/fcover.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=29 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081022114050/http://www.screenindia.com/old/20020426/fcover.html |archivedate=22 October 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHer [[performance]] in her debut film was noticed in film circles and she received offers. She later became famous in 1986 for her role in the film ''[[Ilzaam]]'' opposite another debutant, [[Govinda (actor)|Govinda]]. She made a popular pairing with Govinda and starred with him in 14 movies and some of their films include ''[[Love 86]]'' (1986), ''[[Khudgarz]]'' (1987), ''[[Hatya]]'' (1988) and ''[[Taaqatwar]]'' (1989). She had 5 hits opposite [[Chunkey Pandey]], such as ''[[Aag Hi Aag]]'' (1987), ''[[Paap Ki Duniya]]'' (1988), ''[[Khatron Ke Khiladi (1988 film)|Khatron Ke Khiladi]]'' (1988), ''[[Mitti Aur Sona]]'' (1989)  and ''[[Ghar Ka Chiraag]]'' (1989). She also worked in the Bengali film ''Badnaam'' (1990).\n\nShe was also noticed for her appearance in the 1998 film ''[[Kuch Kuch Hota Hai]]'', where she played herself as a [[VJ (media personality)|VJ]]. Her last film was the 1999 ensemble family drama ''[[Hum Saath Saath Hain]]'' in which she played a supporting role. Her last film was the delayed release ''Kasam'' in 2001, opposite [[Chunky Pandey]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/We-had-loads-to-sort-out-before-marriage-Neelam/articleshow/7358538.cms |title=We had loads to sort out before marriage: Neelam |work=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Sameer Soni,Neelam Kothari grace Kallista Spa opening 08.jpg|thumb|right|Neelam Kothari with husband [[Samir Soni]] at grace Kallista Spa opening.|272x272px]] \nIn October 2000, Neelam married Rishi Sethia in Bangkok, son of a businessman from the U.K.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/eyecatchers/story/20001106-actor-neelam-kothari-and-beau-rishi-sethia-get-married-in-bangkok-778400-2000-11-06 |title=Actor Neelam Kothari and beau Rishi Sethia get married in Bangkok |website=India Today |language=en |access-date=17 May 2018}}</ref> Their marriage was short-lived.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/neelam-kothari-splits-with-beau/story-kJLZpgnUpuUGvrSlW74JRL.html |title=Neelam Kothari splits with beau |date=6 November 2009 |work=www.hindustantimes.com |access-date=17 May 2018 |language=en}}</ref> On 24 January 2011, she married actor [[Samir Soni]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-neelam-weds-samir-soni/20110124.htm |title=Samir Soni weds Neelam |date=24 January 2011 |work=Rediff}}</ref> After 2 years of marriage, they decided to adopt a daughter on 2 September 2013 and named her Ahana.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Maheshwri |first1=Neha |title=Neelam and Samir Soni adopt a baby girl |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Neelam-and-Samir-Soni-have-adopted-a-baby-girl-named-Ahana/articleshow/22222260.cms |website=[[The Times of India]] |accessdate=17 April 2016 |date=2 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Other works==\nNeelam featured in [[Bina Mistry]]'s ''Hot Hot Hot'' music video,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/1999/99jan09/saturday/head6.htm |title=The Tribune...Saturday Plus Head |website=www.tribuneindia.com |access-date=3 August 2017}}</ref> a song that is part of a compilation of dance hits in the 1995 BMG release, titled ''Channel [V] Hits: The Ultimate Dance Collection''. The song became a hit when it was featured as part of the soundtrack of ''[[Bend It Like Beckham]]'' (2002).\n\n==Controversy==\nIn 1998, Neelam was charged with poaching two blackbucks in Kankani during the filming of ''Hum Saath Saath Hain'' along with co-stars [[Salman Khan]], [[Saif Ali Khan]], [[Sonali Bendre]] and [[Tabu (actress)|Tabu]]. A lower court charged her with the others under the Wildlife Act and the IPC. She had filed a revision petition before a sessions court which discharged her of Section 51 (causing harm to wildlife) of the Wildlife Act and both of 147 (punishment for rioting) and 149 (unlawful assembly of persons) of the Indian Penal Code. The Rajasthan state government then filed a revision petition before the Rajasthan high court, which again added Section 149 against her, which it had dropped. In December 2012, the Jodhpur court summoned her along with all the accused for commencement of the trial with the revised charges on 4 February 2013. She was acquitted by the CJM court at Jhodpur on 5 April 2018.\n\n==Jewellery designing==\nEven while pursuing her career in acting, she was interested in jewellery designing and was involved in her family business. She pursued a formal course in jewellery-designing<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.jewellerycraze.com/top-jewellery-designers-in-india/ |title=Top 15 Jewellery Designers In India You Must Know |date=11 July 2017 |website=Jewellery Craze |language=en-US |access-date=27 December 2018}}</ref> in Mumbai and, after quitting films in 2001, started out commercially on her own under the name Neelam Jewels.<ref>[http://archive.gulfnews.com/articles/04/10/27/137191.html Gulfnews: The many faces of Neelam Kothari<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> She opened a showroom in Mumbai in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.verveonline.com/27/spotlight/neelam/neelam.shtml |title=Spotlight - Neelam Jewels |work=verveonline.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090301132349/http://www.verveonline.com/27/spotlight/neelam/neelam.shtml |archivedate=1 March 2009 }}</ref> She then launched her jewellery store in Mumbai on 25 August 2011 under the name Neelam Kothari Fine Jewels.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n!scope=\"col\"| Year\n!scope=\"col\"| Title\n!scope=\"col\"| Role\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Jawaani]]''\n|Sanam\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 1986\n| ''[[Ilzaam]]''\n|Aarti\n|\n|-\n|''Andaz Pyar Ka''\n|\n|\n|-\n|''[[Love 86]]''\n|Esha\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1987\n| ''[[Aag Hi Aag]]''\n|Aarti\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Khudgarz]]''\n|Jyoti\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\" | 1988\n| ''[[Taaqatwar]]''\n|Bijli\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Hatya]]''\n|Sapna\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Waqt Ki Awaz]]''\n|Dancer, Singer\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Ghar Mein Ram Gali Mein Shyam]]''\n|Jaya\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Khatron Ke Khiladi (1988 film)|Khatron Ke Khiladi]]''\n|Sunita\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Paap Ki Duniya]]''\n|Aarti\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Sindoor]]''\n|Lalita Kapoor\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | 1989\n| ''[[Gharana (1989 film)|Gharana]]''\n|Lalita\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Do Qaidi]]''\n|Neelu\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Ghar Ka Chiraag]]''\n|Kiran\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Hum Bhi Insaan Hain (1989 film)|Hum Bhi Insaan Hain]]''\n|Rekha\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Mitti Aur Sona]]''\n|Anupama\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"12\" | 1990\n| ''Vishnu Devaa''\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Mandira]]''\n| \n|[[Bengali language|Bengali]] film\n|-\n| ''[[Badnam]]''\n| Kajol\n|[[Bengali language|Bengali]] film\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Shankara (1991 film)|Shankara]]''\n| Seema\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Doodh Ka Karz]]''\n|Reshma\n|\n|-\n|''Upkar Dhoodhache''\n|Reshma\n|[[Marathi language|Marathi]] film\n|-\n| ''[[Chor Pe Mor]]''\n|Ritu\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Amiri Garibi]]''\n|Jyoti\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Agneepath (1990 film)|Agneepath]]''\n| Siksha Chavan\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Zakhm]]''\n|Aarti\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Billoo Badshah]]''\n|Jyoti\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Farz Ki Jung]]''\n|Kavita\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Dost Garibon Ka]]''\n|Rekha\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | 1991\n| ''Kasak''\n| Divya\n|\n|-\n| ''Meet Mere Man Ke''\n|\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Ranbhoomi]]''\n| Neelam\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Indrajeet]]''\n| Neelam\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Afsana Pyaar Ka]]''\n| Nikita\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 1992\n| ''[[Ek Ladka Ek Ladki]]''\n| Renu / Rani\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Khule-Aam]]''\n| Priya\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Sahebzaade]]''\n| Chinar\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Laat Saab]]''\n| Anju / Mona\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" | 1993\n| ''[[Parampara (1993 film)|Parampara]]''\n| Sapna\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1995\n| ''[[Santaan]]''\n|Asha\n|\n|-\n| ''Antim Nyay''\n|Rekha\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 1996\n| ''[[Ek Tha Raja]]''\n|Shilpa\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Sauda (film)|Sauda]]''\n|Jyoti\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Aadithya]]''\n| \n| [[Kannada language|Kannada]] film\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Mohabbat Aur Jung]]''\n| Priya\n|\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Kuch Kuch Hota Hai]]''\n| Herself as VJ Neelam\n| Special Appearance\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Hum Saath-Saath Hain: We Stand United]]''\n| Sangeeta\n|\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''Pattar Aur Payal''\n|\n|\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Kasam (2001 film)|Kasam]]''\n| Bindiya\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{com